de holds, the pirates will learn fear of honest dark; if it falters, the Lamplands will count lanterns not by number but by names cut short.\",\n      \"objectives\": [\n        \"Meet Tamas at a Lamplands signal tower and receive the coded slate of pirate routes.\",\n        \"Deliver the slate to Sorev Katch at Windward Bastion and convince him to authorize a decoy lantern play.\",\n        \"Help the League of Lanterns run a controlled blackout to funnel pirate skiffs into a Warden ambuscade.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Tamas Eelwick\", \"lines\": \"You know how a veil should fall when the Current runs soft, Tairn—the way it drapes itself smooth as eel-skin and the light in it sighs toward harbor. Tonight it folded like oil on ice, slick on slick, and the code in the peel wasn't ours, though it tried to sing our tune with a sour harmony that tasted like rusted chain. Someone with dock-rights and an honest berth is holding a lantern crooked on purpose, and their crookedness lays a mouth where no chain-house lantern should, a Tenth Mouth with teeth. I followed the flash-phrases through three towers and a blackout pocket, and every step I took the shadows laughed like men who think they know our lanes better than we do. I don't like it, Tairn, and I don't like how my hands shake even as I steady the hood, because fear makes fools and heroes from the same wood and I am tired of splinters. Take this slate; it is scratched in the League’s short-hands and bruised with oil, and I tried to clean it, but the message won't be pretty no matter how you polish it, because it names a path cut right under the Bastion's nose. I came to you because you read lamp-talk with your shoulders as much as your eyes, and because when the water goes black you remember who needs hauling first. If Windward won't move on glow alone, we will feed them truth and then we will set a darkness we own and a net behind it, and if my light fails in my hands, your hook wi