ng to your coat; I will not hand you back to the dark without the tools to bite it. Tell Katch we want muster stairs cleared and storm-rigs checked twice, and tell the League we want their code-leaf kept clean—one signal for rescue and one for net, no cleverness that gets a worker dead. You take this coil with knots the Knotted Wives swore to hold in foul water, and you make sure those boats that think they own the Current find themselves owned by a city that remembers its drowned. If anyone tries to turn blame onto labor after, I will stand in the Court of Echoing Shells and let the shells keen their throats dry while I call names, because we keep receipts in salt and scar both.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Tairn Latch\", \"lines\": \"We run it tight and we run it cold, no flourishes and no heroics that draw more blood than the tide already taxes; one blackout, one hook, one haul, and no one goes home with a story prettier than the work. The Current will take them where we ask if we sing the light true, and where we ask is toward a net set by Wardens who remember how to pull together instead of apart. Captain Katch, I will put my name and my breath on this, and if anything tilts crooked because a signal cracked or a courage failed, I will stand to it as fault is mine before any shell or judge asks, because I am done letting ghosts speak for me. Tamas, your slate warms my palm like a fulgurite clenched during an oath, and that heat says a thing I hate to hear: that there is honesty in this danger, and we must meet it honestly or let it eat us like soft wood. Isha, your coil sits heavy across my shoulder like an extra promise, and I will use it first for the man most likely to be forgotten, because if the city is an instrument as the Conclave claims, then the note that makes it true is the one that saves a name. We go now before the veils change their fold, and when we return we will eat eel stew with oil still on our sleeves and talk quietly about the night the city decided to own its darkness.\"}\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"C1\", \"title\": \"Confess the old blackout and ask for joint command\", \"text\": \"You stand before Sorev Katch not as a runner of errands but as a man with a weight, and you lay the weight down where it can be measured. You tell him about the night years ago when the League ran a blackout to spare the Lamplands and how a Warden cutter went down in the confusion, and how one man did not come back up, and how that ghost has walked beside your shadow ever since. You do not make excuses; you name names where it hurts you, and you offer the shape of your failure as a map to avoid, not a badge to kiss. You ask for joint command of the decoy play—Lanterns on light, Wardens on steel, Dockers on rescue lines—so that no single hand turns the city blind without others feeling the same dark on their skin. You promise to take public fault if anything goes wrong again, and you ask him to take public credit if it goes right, because you know what it costs a guard to admit he needed a lamplighter. Five sentences do not empty a heart, but they do set an edge that can cut through habit and pride.\", \"outcome\": \"Katch listens with the stillness of a tide before it turns, and when you finish he rests his palm flat on the stormglass table as if to keep the sea from rising up through it. He tells you that he respects a man who brings his own gallows to the square and asks for a fair rope, and he does not smile when he grants joint command, but he nods to your spine as if it were an iron bar he could know. He multiplies safety crews and sets a second line of cutters a breath farther down the Current, a gesture that will not show in any ledger but will show in the number of lungs that still draw morning air. The operation runs with a tense clarity that feels like holding your breath under clean water, and when the pirates bite the dark and find net instead of passage, the first shout goes up from a W