 a thinness to his acknowledging glance, as if he smelled something withheld and decided to set it aside for later, carefully wrapped and labeled. Tamas grips your shoulder in a dark corner and thanks you in five careful words that carry more oil than comfort, and he does not ask what else you could have said, because he knows, because he was there when you could have said it. In the quiet after, the city sleeps and your guilt does not; it prowls the rafters of your skull like a lantern moth seeking light, and though no one dead comes knocking, you hear water in your dreams and wake with your hand clawed for a chain. The mission succeeds without public confession, the Lamplands are uncut, and yet you mark the price in the small places where a man’s breath goes shallow when he passes the Bastion.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C3\", \"title\": \"Widen the net with Dockers’ safety lines and marsh ferries\", \"text\": \"You leave the Bastion with your plan and double back through Chainmouth to the House of Weights, where you rattle the old meteoric slate with your knuckles until Isha’s crew look up and remember why the stone was bought. You petition the Syndicate to muster extra riggers and marsh ferries under loan, not to fight, not to glory, but to stand in the black between boat and death, and you make the case that a city is best measured by how many come home. You send runners to the Saltstep to tap village ferrymen who ride swells like breath, and you ask the Knotted Wives for three coils sung to float a man who is too tired to sing for himself. You show Lantern code in the open to Dockers who have earned it by scar and oath, and you insist the Wardens make room on their gunwales for rescue hands instead of extra pikes. You stretch the plan wide without letting it thin, and you own the risk that wider nets catch more eyes, because you would rather be seen doing good than unseen doing less than you might.\", \"outcome\": \"The docks bloom with quiet readiness: coils pile like sea-snakes asleep, ferries rock with lanterns hooded to finger-width, and riggers tie knots that remember storms. When the blackout curtain falls, it falls onto a harbor laced with safety like a web spun by a patient spider, and when the pirates blunder into Katch’s steel, they find themselves dragged not only by hooks but lifted by hands that refuse to let even enemies sink unnamed. A single Warden slips on a wet plank and goes under, and a marshwife’s coil finds him at the second blink, hauling him up with a breath still inside, and the Bastion’s cheer is ragged and honest. House Saltvein’s watchers mark the unusual muster and twitch like crabs in a bucket, and their report will cause you later trouble in tariffs and talk, but tonight the Lamplands keep their porches and their stories, and the Dockers make a feast from saved bread. Katch grumbles about chaos even as he signs a line in his log that reads fewer dead than expected, and Isha slaps your back so hard your lungs ring, and the League marks a code phrase in their books for labor lights that saved more than cargo. The city learns to see rescue as part of war, not its aftermath, and you feel your father’s name sit a fraction straighter in your chest.\"}\n      ],\n      \"connections\": {\"previous\": [\"M2\"], \"next\": [\"M4\"]},\n      \"rewards\": [\n        {\"type\": \"Item\", \"description\": \"League of Lanterns code-leaf: a pocket primer for reading advanced harbor signals.\"},\n        {\"type\": \"Reputation\", \"description\": \"+Small with River Wardens and League of Lanterns.\"},\n        {\"type\": \"Coin and Supply\", \"description\": \"5 silver and a flask of high-grade lamp oil.\"}\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}"